strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:
>
>To clarify Peter Boucher's post, the reason permissions were put on the
>ripem files, and they now require an account, is to control distribution
>to the U.S. and Canada, in order not to violate the Munitions Act. Since
>ripem uses DES, it must obey the same distribution rules DES has, in the
>U.S.
>
>My guess, therefore, is that when ripem is released, which is imminent,
>it will only be available formally to users in the U.S. and Canada and
>some sort of permission/account or other control mechanism will
>continue. In addition to the Munitions Act issues, those who receive
>ripem will have to agree to the RSAREF agreement, and thus some assent
>mechanism is going to be required.

If the package is any good, it will take approximately 24 hours for it
to appear for anonymous FTP all over the world.

